{
  "text": "Lower breast cancer screening rates have been associated with later stage cancer at diagnosis, and greater morbidity and mortality among underserved populations, including Medicaid enrollees [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Recent studies have further reinforced the growing evidence of geographic disparities in access to care and preventive services, such as cancer screening [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Various factors are associated with cancer screening disparities, including density of or distance to the closest provider, residential segregation, literacy, education, and socioeconomic status [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] .",
